Eat beef (Cow Mata) allowed in Hinduism.
Rigveda (10/85/13) declares: "On the occasion of the marriage of a girl, oxen and cows are sacrificed".
Rigveda (06/17/1) states that "Indra used to eat beef, veal, horse and buffalo."
Manusmriti (Chapter 5 / Verse 30) says: "It is not sinful to eat the flesh of edible animals, because Brahma has created both the eaters and the edibles."
Maharishi Yagyavalkya says in Shatpath Brahmin (1/1/2/21) that, "I eat meat because it is very soft and delicious".
Apastamb Grihsutram (1/3/10) says: "The cow must be sacrificed upon the arrival of a guest, on the occasion of 'Shraddha' of ancestors and on the occasion of a marriage."

Margaux S Milchen.The Treaty of Peace and Friendship between the United States of America and the Bey and the subjects of Tripoli de Barbary, signed at Tripoli on November 4, 1796, Article 11 was established as a matter of controversy between the translations to English and Arabic of the Treaty. Adams criticized claims to universal authority made by the Roman Catholic Church, which may well be the basis on which the wording of Article 11 was based.

While it is true that Adams signed the aforementioned Treaty, it should be noted that he also signed the Declaration of Independence and the Bill of Rights; both serve to further support Adams' words as misunderstood. That the Congress has unanimously signed the Treaty is absurd when one recognizes the problem of full translation.

John Adams was a devout Christian and an independent thinker. In a letter to Benjamin Rush, Adams attributed to religion the success of his ancestors since his migration to the New World in the 1630s. He also believed that the regular service of the church was beneficial to the moral sense of man. In 1796, Adams denounced the deistic criticism of political critic Thomas Paine to Christianity in The Age of Reason, saying: "The Christian religion is, above all religions that once prevailed or existed in ancient or modern times, religion of wisdom, virtue, equity and humanity, let Blackguard Paine say what he wants ".

In the light of Adams's Christianity, it is very unlikely that translations from English to Arabic were accurately transcribed. It is much more plausible that he rejected the claims of "universal authority" proclaimed by the Roman Catholic Church than anything remotely dismissing the foundation on the Christian religion.

Adams served twice as Vice President under President George Washington. comment_text: and The Indian Army Band shows up at Drass WHEN WAS THE WAR? The Kargil war, which began in May 1999, was announced after the infiltration of Pakistani troops and Kashmiri militants in the Kargil district of Jammu and Kashmir and the Line of Control (LOC). The intrusion into the area, which divided the Indian territory of Ladakh from the northern areas of the state, had been a complete surprise to the Indian army and Operation Vijay was immediately launched to drive our enemies out of the Kargil sector. Pakistani Soldiers MASTERMIND BEHIND THE ATTACK Pervez Musharraf, the then Chief of the Pakistani Army, is said to be the brain box behind the attack. Musharraf carefully traced the intrusion plan, without any details of then Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif. He was supported and assisted by the General Leutenant Mohammed Aziz. It is said that Musharraf executed the plan, while Atal Bihari Vajpayee had responded to Nawaz Sharif's invitation to Lahore and where the duo signed the Lahore declaration. Conventional modes of warfare WAY OF FIGHT Well equipped with weapons of war, both sides were prepared to launch attacks on each other. The battle of 18,000 feet in the rocky terrain was fought under extremely low temperatures, in a conventional manner, despite the fact that both parties possess nuclear weapons. India placed five infantry divisions, five independent brigades and 44 battalions of paramilitary troops in Kashmir and deployed more than 60 frontline aircraft. Former Prime Minister Manmohan Singh with army and air force officers greet at the Gateway of India in Vijay Diwas. THE AIR FORCE OF INDIA On May 24, 1999, it was decided that the Indian Air Force (IAF) would join the operation. However, it was emphasized that the IAF would not cross the LOC at all costs. The IAF launched bomb attacks against the enemy within its limit. Tiger Hill, one of the highest peaks in the Drass-Kargil area of ‚Äã‚Äãthe state, became the focal point during the war. After a fierce war of more than sixty days, and with the support of the international community, India regained Tiger Hill and pushed Pakistani forces into its territory. Schoolchildren show a national flag on an Indian army tank to commemorate the day. INTERNATIONAL RESPONSE TO THE CONFLICT The infiltration of Pakistan into India and the military confrontation were deeply criticized by many countries and attracted the intervention of the United States in the crisis. According to a report in the Daily Times, a leading newspaper in Pakistan, India won the confidence of the United States, while Pakistan "lost its credibility with India and Pakistan." The international community began to put pressure on Pakistani forces and threatened to withdraw or face isolation. Russia and Israel also came forward to support India's position. comment_text:
The 10 most played tricks by the media to control the masses:

1. Project 'everything is fine' in default mode, even if they are not, lulling people into complacency. (routine 'news' damping, sports, celebrity gossip, science, etc.). This technique is used by shepherds that raise sheep for slaughter.

2. Emphasize the individual identity (nationality, religion, state, etc.) to ensure the subconscious separation (the politics of division and rule).

3. Contractile 'voice of the poor' / 'power of protest', etc., although these do not exist. This tricks people into 'thinking' that they are in control.

4. Stage events ('astro turfing', 'shills', 'false witnesses', 'crisis actors', etc.), whether to make 'mass movement', create paranoia or extreme fear, or distract the masses of real problems.

5. Use sports, celebrities and gossip, etc., to deviate from real problems (and mold public opinion).

6. Play key supporting role for large sponsored events of false flag, cheating, etc. (for wars, laws, create fear, distract, etc.) Many of your favorite news anchors and journalists are, in fact, establishment (intelligence) officers.

7. Represent the government as a victim of the crime (trap, assault, etc.), so that the people do not protest later against the draconian laws against themselves.

8. Manufacturing extreme fear, through exaggerated claims of diseases, the power of the enemy, terrorism, etc., (to support wars, desensitize or divide people, for example)

9. The "media blackout" (not informing leads to ignorance or dullness) or reporting malevolence (stereotypes or demonization): the most common control technique.

10. Finally, and most reserved, the media are owned by a handful of companies and suppress other sources of information. The media forms the 'matrix' - a network of illusions to deceive the masses, and together with 'politics' are the secret property of banking families.

The next time your favorite news media "break news," ask yourself: "Is this true, or is this your last cheating / deception / false flag operation"?

In India, we change lanes without indicating, we drive drunk, we stop behind the red stop sign and jump over them without thinking twice about the serious implications. The absence of emergency lanes on the roads. People do not give space to Ambulance and other emergency vehicles. I also lost my mother in an ambulance only because few people had more important places to reach and blocked the road. Believe me that your management perspective would completely change when you are in a situation like that.

So I fully support the government's decision to make fines go hand in hand with global standards and I hope that all traffic violators get what they really deserve.

Cow in Hinduism:

Eat beef (Cow Mata) allowed in Hinduism.
Rigveda (10/85/13) declares: "On the occasion of the marriage of a girl, oxen and cows are sacrificed".
Rigveda (06/17/1) states that "Indra used to eat beef, veal, horse and buffalo."
Manusmriti (Chapter 5 / Verse 30) says: "It is not sinful to eat the flesh of edible animals, because Brahma has created both the eaters and the edibles."
Maharishi Yagyavalkya says in Shatpath Brahmin (1/1/2/21) that, "I eat meat because it is very soft and delicious".
Apastamb Grihsutram (1/3/10) says: "The cow must be sacrificed upon the arrival of a guest, on the occasion of 'Shraddha' of ancestors and on the occasion of a marriage."
Vashistha Dharmasutra (11/34) writes: "If a Brahmin refuses to eat the meat that is offered to him on the occasion of 'Shraddha' or worship, he goes to hell."

comment_text:
Kevin Gaskin We invite you to look at the Bill of Rights, the US Constitution. UU And in the Declaration of Independence, but you will not find anything about "separation of Church and State" in any of them.

Thomas Jefferson wrote a letter to the Danbury Baptist Association in 1802 to answer a letter from them, asking why he would not proclaim national days of fasting and thanksgiving, as Washington and Adams had done before him. The letter contains the phrase "wall of separation between church and state," which led to the erroneous 'short hand' for the Establishment Clause (US Constitution, Bill of Rights, Amendment I, Article III) that we use today.

"Why do I have freedom of religion ...?" The answer is in the documents of the Congress regarding our Constitution as we know it today. The process of drafting the First Amendment made the intention of the Founders very clear; Before they approved the final draft, the First Amendment went through almost a dozen different iterations and extensive discussions.

"We do not want in the United States what we had in Britain: we do not want a denomination with the Nation, we will not all be Catholics, Anglicans or any other denomination, we want the principles of God, but we do not want a single denomination managing the Nation".

This attempt was well understood, as evidenced by the courts' decisions after the First Amendment. In 1799 the court declared: "By our form of government, the Christian religion is the established religion, and all sects and denominations of Christians are placed on an equal footing."

One must realize that our Founding Fathers were struggling to achieve "freedom of religion" due to the oppressive authority of the Roman Catholic Church. It was not only Great Britain but most of Europe that fell under the astonishing authority of Roman Catholicism. Our Founding Fathers set out to recognize the many denominations of Christianity. In addition, they intended to recognize each denomination equally, instead of granting control power over a single denomination. Here is the misinterpretation of the reckless "shorthand" known as "separation of Church and State."

A more accurate statement is likely "separation of denominations of Church and State." Such an interpretation is fully supported by the documents of the Congress in reference to the declaration: "We do not want in the United States what we had in Britain: we do not do it". he wants a denomination running the Nation. Not all of us will be Catholics, Anglicans or any other denomination. We want the principles of God, but we do not want a single denomination managing the Nation ".

Regarding the statement, "The majority of our founding fathers were agnostics", that simply is not true. It is a general statement proclaimed by those who oppose religion in general. Yes, there were agnostics in those days, but they were not as frequent as claimed. Thomas Paine was a political activist, philosopher, political theorist and English-American revolutionary. Although he is considered one of our Founding Fathers, he was rejected for his known agnostic beliefs.

John Adams is another wrongly accused of being an agnostic. However, here is a quote from President Adams in reference to Thomas Paine; "The Christian religion is, over all the religions that once prevailed or existed in ancient or modern times, the religion of wisdom, virtue, equity and humanity, that the Black Guardian Paine says what he wants." I think you will agree with his words regarding Mr. Paine are more than enough to dispel any claim of their agnostic beliefs.

comment_text:
Q1) Is the GDP data distorted?

- Yes they are. They are not accurate. They are being tricked into promoting a lie.

Q2) Can you prove that the GDP data is falsified?

- Until January 2015, India's economy was witnessing its growth since the mid-1980s. And then the magic happened. The Central Bureau of Statistics (CSO) changed the way it calculates GDP by saying that it was necessary to do so taking into account global practices. As a result, India surpassed China and became the fastest growing economy. In 2013-14, our economy grew to 6.9%, instead of 4.7%, which CSO data showed earlier. Even the country's leading economic adviser, Arvind Subramanian, said: "I am baffled by the new GDP growth numbers." The revised figures show that GDP growth increased from 4.7% to 5.1% for 2012-13 and from 5% to 6.9% for 2013-14. This means an acceleration in GDP growth of 1.9 percentage points in 2013-14, simply by comparing the new figures over time. " He also said that "these figures, especially the acceleration in 2013-14, are at odds with other features of the macroeconomy. Almost all economics experts, working inside or outside the government (including Raghuram Rajan), questioned the GDP figures, since they found that the basic realities reflected a completely opposite picture, the new GDP figures seemed completely in conflict with other economic indicators.According to R Nagraj, an independent member of the subcommittee who examined the new methodology for estimating the product, the version adopted by The Central Stastical Organization differed dramatically from the report finalized by the subcommittee in September 2014.

Q3) What happens with the latest GDP data published after demonetization?

- They are also pretended. Although the performance of some sectors has been better compared to its performance in previous quarters, the great improvement in private consumption (almost double) seems highly doubtful amidst the cash crisis during demonetization. It seems that the CSO has not been able to map the demonetization effect in its data. Both the government and RBI have also been saying (as are some of their sensible critics) that the effect of demonetization can be traced in a longer time frame. In addition, the CSO revised DOWN estimates of Q3 of 2015-16 by 0.3 percentage points to 6.9% from 7.2% previously, which led to a considerable improvement in the Q3 2016-17 figures. For those who do not find it surprising, the CSO revised the UP Q1 and Q2 estimates from 2015-16. This downward revision of T3 of 2015-16 has helped to restrict the effect of demonetization on the figures.

P4) I can not understand anything. Why?

- You can not get it. You are not a statistician or an economist. Whenever reports and complaints like these arise, hurry a bit on the Internet beyond Facebook and Twitter, and read about basic things and what experts have to say about them.

Q5) But Modi ji says that the experts do not know anything. Do not you think he's right?

- After Hindutva, the best tactic Modi ji has is disinformation. He has convinced people to believe that experts do not know anything. He misinforms people who do not know anything, but to believe him. They do not have enough time or will to discover the truth. And when experts question his and he's claims, people never understand what the experts say because they are not educated enough to understand.

Apastamb Grihsutram (1/3/10) says: "The cow must be sacrificed upon the arrival of a guest, on the occasion of 'Shraddha' of ancestors and on the occasion of a marriage."
